  "prompt": "When should I prune my roses?",
  "response": "Pruning roses is essential for promoting healthy growth, improving air circulation, and encouraging blooms. The best time to prune roses generally depends on your climate and the type of rose you have, but here are some general guidelines:\n\n1. **Late Winter to Early Spring**: In most temperate regions, the best time to prune most rose varieties is in late winter or early spring, typically when the plants are still dormant but before new growth begins. This is usually just after the last frost date in your area.\n\n2. **Look for Signs of New Growth**: A good rule of thumb is to wait until you see the buds swelling on the stems. This is often an indication that the plant is ready to wake up from dormancy.\n\n3. **Specific Types of Roses**:\n   - **Hybrid Tea and Grandiflora Roses**: Prune in late winter or early spring, cutting back about one-third to two-thirds of the plant.\n   - **Floribunda Roses**: Similar to hybrid teas, prune in early spring, removing dead wood and shaping the bush.\n   - **Climbing Roses**: Prune after flowering in the summer for most varieties, but some can be lightly pruned in late winter to remove dead or weak stems.\n   - **Shrub Roses**: Generally pruned in spring to maintain shape, removing any dead or diseased wood.\n\n4. **Avoid Pruning in Fall**: Pruning in the fall can stimulate new growth that may not survive the winter.\n\nAlways use clean, sharp tools, and make clean cuts to reduce the risk of disease. It's also a good idea to research the specific requirements for the type of roses you are growing, as different varieties can have different needs.",
